        "secs": 18,
        "core": true,
        "say": "Sometimes the conflict is not yours, yet you are the calm one in the room. Two people you care about are stuck, talking past each other, and they look to you for help. This lesson is a gentle introduction to one caring role you can play: helping each person feel heard, without becoming a judge who decides who is right. It is about lowering the heat, not handing down a verdict.",
        "simpler": "Sometimes two people you care about are fighting, and you are the calm one they turn to. This lesson shows one kind way to help: making sure each person feels listened to, instead of you deciding who wins.",
        "deeper": "The role described here is closer to a facilitator than an arbiter. A facilitator tends to the quality of the conversation itself, the safety, the pacing, the turn-taking, rather than the content of who is correct. Naming this role for yourself early helps you resist the strong social pull to evaluate, advise, or rescue, which usually escalates rather than settles a dispute between two other people."
