        "core": true,
        "say": "The first thing that helps is staying neutral on purpose. When you are not one of the people in conflict, you can hold space so each side feels safe to speak. In Nonviolent Communication, a person who helps with a conflict is often called a mediator, and their job is to help the parties hear each other and deepen their mutual understanding, not to take a side. The moment you tilt toward one person, the other tends to stop trusting the conversation.",
        "simpler": "Try to stay in the middle on purpose. Your job is to help both people feel safe enough to talk, not to back one of them. The second someone feels you are on the other person's team, they usually shut down.",
        "deeper": "Perceived impartiality is what gives a third party their usefulness. In the Nonviolent Communication tradition, the mediator's task is described as helping each party hear the other and deepen mutual understanding rather than judging. Neutrality is not coldness or indifference; it is a disciplined, warm even-handedness in which you extend the same curiosity and care to each person, so neither experiences you as an opponent."
