        "simpler": "There is a simple four-part way of talking that Marshall Rosenberg created, called Nonviolent Communication. The four parts are: what happened, how I feel, what I need, and what I would like. You can nudge each person to talk this way instead of just blaming.",
        "deeper": "The four components, observation, feeling, need, and request, are designed to separate description from evaluation. An observation reports what a camera would capture, kept apart from interpretation; a feeling is named without disguised judgment; a need points to a universal human requirement such as respect or safety; and a request is specific and free of demand. As a facilitator you rarely lecture on the model, you simply steer expression toward feelings and needs, which tend to invite connection rather than defense."
