        "simpler": "Here is a simple back-and-forth. One person talks, the other repeats back what they heard before answering, and the first person says whether that was right. Then they swap. You just keep it slow and make sure each gets a turn. People relax once they feel truly understood, even when they still disagree.",
        "deeper": "This structured paraphrasing sequence, sometimes called reflective or active listening, interrupts the usual pattern in which each party rehearses a rebuttal instead of listening. By requiring an accuracy check, did I understand you correctly, before any response, the loop creates evidence of being understood, which lowers physiological arousal and defensiveness. The facilitator's main contributions are pacing and turn protection, ensuring reflection precedes reply and that confirmation actually occurs rather than being assumed."
